<div id="review_2009133204" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2009133204" />
    <a title="Blair Hodgkinson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12641918-blair-hodgkinson"><img alt="Blair Hodgkinson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1408074471p2/12641918.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2009133204?book_show_action=true">Jun 13, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Blair Hodgkinson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Blair Hodgkinson" href="/user/show/12641918-blair-hodgkinson">Blair Hodgkinson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670067244" href="/book/show/1363603.In_Defense_Of_Atheism">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12641918-blair-hodgkinson?shelf=history-social-history">history-social-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12641918-blair-hodgkinson?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2009133204" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5063559537412752034">This is a riveting (if a little disjointed) vivisection of the three main religions of the world. It points out their many inconsistencies and moral shortcomings, vividly portrays both their similarities and their irreconcilability. The author takes a stand for reason and issues a call to arms for a new post-monotheist secularism to fight the rising tide of religious extremism. This was written in the early years of the War on Terror, and so it spends much time on the rise of Islamic extremism, </span>
  <span id="freeText5063559537412752034" style="display:none">This is a riveting (if a little disjointed) vivisection of the three main religions of the world. It points out their many inconsistencies and moral shortcomings, vividly portrays both their similarities and their irreconcilability. The author takes a stand for reason and issues a call to arms for a new post-monotheist secularism to fight the rising tide of religious extremism. This was written in the early years of the War on Terror, and so it spends much time on the rise of Islamic extremism, but I can't help wondering if the author wrote this book in the current climate if he would not be just as concerned about the rise of increasingly extreme Christians too. (He does give enough attention to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict to say he has expressed ample concern about the ambitions of Jewish nationalism.) An interesting, provocative and sometimes outright incisive read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5063559537412752034" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


